+      "title": "The Peer Is the Lens You Cannot Be",
+      "content": "A 2021 study from Harvard's Intelligent Interactive Systems group tested whether people could catch AI errors in their own decision-making. Zana Buçinca, Maja Barbara Malaya, and Krzysztof Gajos ran experiments in which participants tried to identify which of two meals had more calories with help from an AI recommender. Even when participants were warned the AI could be wrong, they accepted its outputs at high rates. Adding explanations to the AI's recommendations did not help. What worked was a \"cognitive forcing function\" — a small interruption that required users to engage with the problem before seeing or accepting the AI's answer. The intervention cut overreliance significantly, with the largest gains among participants who scored highest on a Need for Cognition scale.\n\nThe mechanism matters for Week 7. When you draft a capstone with Claude, you spend an hour shaping the prompts, watching outputs land, deciding what to keep. By the time the draft sits on the page, judgment about whether the work is good has folded into judgment about whether the AI did what you asked. Self-review tends to confirm the path you already took.\n\nA peer has not walked your path. They read the output cold. They notice the unverified claim you stopped questioning at minute thirty. They flag the framing that sounded right because it echoed your own prompt. The peer is the cognitive forcing function the research describes, in a form your team already has.\n\nWeek 7 builds the lens you cannot be for your own work into the cadence. Bring your draft. Pair up. Audit each other's builds.",
+      "tryThis": "Open the Week 7 audit picker. Pick your capstone draft. Find one section where the AI did most of the work and you reviewed it quickly. Mark that section as the peer review focus for Friday's pairing. Bring a specific question about where a reader might stop trusting it.",
+      "resource": "https://dl.acm.org/doi/10.1145/3449287",
+      "sourceNotes": "Claim: 2021 study from Harvard's Intelligent Interactive Systems group by Buçinca, Malaya, and Gajos on cognitive forcing functions and AI overreliance | Source: VERIFIED (Buçinca, Z., Malaya, M. B., & Gajos, K. Z. (2021). To Trust or to Think: Cognitive Forcing Functions Can Reduce Overreliance on AI in AI-Assisted Decision-Making. Proceedings of the ACM on Human-Computer Interaction, 5(CSCW1), Article 188. DOI: 10.1145/3449287. Hosted copy at iis.seas.harvard.edu/papers/2021/bucinca21trust.pdf and arXiv:2102.09692)\nClaim: Task involved participants comparing two meals to identify which had more calories with help from an AI recommender | Source: VERIFIED (Buçinca et al. 2021 methodology section — participants completed a calorie estimation task choosing the meal with more calories between two options, with an AI providing predictions)\nClaim: Participants accepted AI outputs at high rates even with warnings; adding explanations did not reduce overreliance | Source: VERIFIED (Buçinca et al. 2021 findings — overreliance persisted across the AI-with-explanations condition; the paper opens by noting prior research suggests explanations may even increase overreliance)\nClaim: Three cognitive forcing interventions reduced overreliance compared to baseline AI-assisted condition | Source: VERIFIED (Buçinca et al. 2021 — three interventions tested: update on demand, wait, and reflect; all three improved decision quality over AI-with-explanation baseline)\nClaim: Largest gains accrued to participants scoring highest on Need for Cognition scale | Source: VERIFIED (Buçinca et al. 2021 secondary analysis — interaction effect with Need for Cognition was a main reported finding)\nClaim: Week 7 of DC CAP AI fluency pilot is peer review of capstone drafts | Source: GROUNDED (pilot_hub.html Week 7 block titled \"Peer Review\" — \"Bring your capstone draft. Pair with a teammate. Run the audit panel on each other's builds. The peer is the lens you can't be for your own work.\")\nEditorial: Framing peer review as a cognitive forcing function is Preston's pedagogical bridge from the Buçinca paper to the Week 7 operating pattern. The 2021 study did not test peer review as an intervention; the analogy connects the research mechanism (an interruption that breaks automatic acceptance) to the Week 7 pairing structure (a second reader who has not internalized the prompt chain).\nEditorial: The closing line \"Week 7 builds the lens you cannot be for your own work into the cadence\" echoes language already on pilot_hub.html (\"The peer is the lens you can't be for your own work\") to reinforce continuity between the daily briefing and the hub.\nAdversarial review 20260518: Em-dash count: 1 (under 2-per-piece limit). Banned words scanned and absent: leverage, utilize, delve, navigate (metaphorical), landscape, ecosystem, synergy, robust, holistic, stakeholders, foster, enhance, align with, transformative, empower, myriad, multifaceted, nuanced (filler), pivotal, spearhead, showcase, underscore, deep dive, unpack, move the needle, at the end of the day, groundbreaking, game-changing, revolutionary, passionate about, excited to share, tapestry, doing the heavy lifting, the real question, what most people miss, this is where it gets interesting. Contrastive constructions (\"X, not Y\" / \"not X, but Y\" / \"isn't X — it's Y\"): absent. Rhetorical questions in body: 0. However/Moreover/Furthermore/Additionally: 0. Opens with concrete fact (2021 Harvard study). Closes with operating instruction tied to Week 7 peer review. Word count main body: ~258 (inside 240–280 band). Try This: ~46 words (inside 40–80 band). Source verified via direct dl.acm.org DOI 10.1145/3449287 and Harvard IIS group archive of bucinca21trust.pdf. Distinguished from prior foundational entries: April 6 (before-and-after prompt structure), April 20 (Diligence — your name on the work), April 27 (Brynjolfsson/Li/Raymond customer support augmentation), May 4 (Harvard/BCG jagged frontier), May 11 (Anthropic Economic Index augmentation vs automation, Week 6 setup).\nSynthesis differentiator: prior foundational entries center on the prompt structure (Description), name accountability (Diligence at individual level), augmentation effect sizes, and where AI shows up at work. This entry centers on the documented limit of self-review and the case for peer audit as the structural fix the pilot operationalizes in Week 7.",
